<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,358,1141]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,898,925]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lochman, in Lochman &amp; Duncan" authorityYear="1944" box="[340,558,899,925]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphiscidae" genus="Blountina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eleanora">
<emphasis box="[340,558,899,925]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Blountina eleanora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was reported from the Deadwood Formation of 
<collectingRegion box="[1108,1262,899,925]" country="United States of America" name="South Dakota" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">South Dakota</collectingRegion>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Stitt, J. H. &amp; Perfetta, P. J." pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="199 - 223" refId="ref24040" refString="Stitt, J. H. &amp; Perfetta, P. J. (2000) Trilobites, biostratigraphy, and lithostratigraphy of the Crepicephalus and Aphelaspis zones, lower Deadwood Formation (Marjuman and Steptoean stages, Upper Cambrian), Black Hills, South Dakota. Journal of Paleontology, 74, 199 - 223. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0022336000031437" type="journal article" year="2000">Stitt &amp; Perfetta (2000</bibRefCitation>
, figs 11.8–11.13), but comparison with the 
<typeStatus box="[766,825,935,961]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">types</typeStatus>
(Pls 26, 27) shows that their specimens are misidentified. As far can be determined from their very small images, the cranidia have very short frontal areas that lack preglabellar fields. The palpebral lobes are located farther forward than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lochman, in Lochman &amp; Duncan" authorityYear="1944" box="[993,1125,1007,1033]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphiscidae" genus="Blountina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eleanora">
<emphasis box="[993,1010,1008,1033]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1025,1125,1007,1033]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">eleanora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the posterior branches of the facial sutures are less divergent, so that the posterolateral projections tapers (exsag., tr.) more rapidly. The associated pygidia (
<bibRefCitation author="Stitt, J. H. &amp; Perfetta, P. J." box="[372,616,1079,1105]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="199 - 223" refId="ref24040" refString="Stitt, J. H. &amp; Perfetta, P. J. (2000) Trilobites, biostratigraphy, and lithostratigraphy of the Crepicephalus and Aphelaspis zones, lower Deadwood Formation (Marjuman and Steptoean stages, Upper Cambrian), Black Hills, South Dakota. Journal of Paleontology, 74, 199 - 223. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0022336000031437" type="journal article" year="2000">Stitt &amp; Perfetta, 2000</bibRefCitation>
, figs 11.11–11.13) are relatively longer and narrower than both small (Pl. 27, fig. 5) and larger (Pl. 27, fig. 1) specimens from 
<bibRefCitation author="Lochman, C. &amp; Duncan, D." box="[737,1066,1115,1141]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 172" refId="ref23573" refString="Lochman, C. &amp; Duncan, D. (1944) Early Upper Cambrian faunas of Central Montana. Geological Society of America Special Papers, 54, 1 - 172. https: // doi. org / 10.1130 / SPE 54 - p 1" type="journal article" year="1944">Lochman &amp; Duncan’s (1944)</bibRefCitation>
<typeStatus box="[1073,1136,1115,1141]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">types</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
